# Views SDK Client — Typed Data Client for Custom Views

## Core Idea

View creator defines schema once in `defineView()`. From that single source of truth: API endpoint + typed SDK client. Supabase-style DX for blockchain-indexed data.

## API Design

```typescript
import { SecondLayer } from "@secondlayer/sdk";

const sl = new SecondLayer({ apiKey: "..." });

// Get a typed client for a specific view table
const swaps = sl.view("dex-swaps").table("swaps");

// Fluent query builder
const { data, meta } = await swaps
  .select("user", "token_in", "amount_in")
  .where("user", "SP123...")
  .where("amount_in", "gte", 1000000)
  .orderBy("_block_height", "desc")
  .limit(20)
  .execute();

// Count
const { count } = await swaps.count().where("token_in", "STX").execute();

// Single row by _id
const row = await swaps.find(42);
```

## Type Safety via Codegen

```bash
sl views pull dex-swaps -o ./src/views.ts
```

Generates from deployed view schema:

```typescript
export interface SwapsRow {
  _id: number;
  _block_height: number;
  _tx_id: string;
  _created_at: string;
  user: string;
  token_in: string;
  token_out: string;
  amount_in: bigint;
}
```

Usage with generics:

```typescript
const swaps = sl.view<SwapsRow>("dex-swaps").table("swaps");
// .where(), .select(), .orderBy() all autocomplete with SwapsRow fields
```

## Query Builder API

```typescript
interface ViewTableClient<T> {
  // Select specific columns (narrows return type)
  select<K extends keyof T>(...cols: K[]): ViewQuery<Pick<T, K>>;

  // Filters
  where(col: keyof T, value: unknown): ViewQuery<T>;
  where(col: keyof T, op: "gt" | "gte" | "lt" | "lte" | "neq", value: unknown): ViewQuery<T>;

  // Sorting
  orderBy(col: keyof T, dir?: "asc" | "desc"): ViewQuery<T>;

  // Pagination
  limit(n: number): ViewQuery<T>;
  offset(n: number): ViewQuery<T>;

  // Execute
  execute(): Promise<{ data: T[]; meta: { total: number; limit: number; offset: number } }>;

  // Shortcuts
  find(id: number): Promise<T | null>;
  count(): ViewCountQuery;
  first(): Promise<T | null>;
}
```

## Backend — No New Work

Existing endpoints already support everything:

| SDK method | HTTP call |
|------------|-----------|
| `.execute()` | `GET /api/views/:name/:table?filters&_sort&_order&_limit&_offset` |
| `.count()` | `GET /api/views/:name/:table/count?filters` |
| `.find(id)` | `GET /api/views/:name/:table/:id` |

SDK is purely a fluent DX layer on top of existing REST API.

## Codegen Flow

```
defineView({ schema }) → deploy → API stores schema
                                      ↓
                          sl views pull <name> -o types.ts
                                      ↓
                          Parse schema → generate TS interfaces
                                      ↓
                          sl.view<GeneratedType>("name").table("table")
```

### Column Type Mapping (schema → TypeScript)

| View schema type | TypeScript type |
|-----------------|-----------------|
| text | string |
| principal | string |
| uint | bigint |
| int | number |
| boolean | boolean |
| timestamp | string (ISO 8601) |
| jsonb | unknown |

## Comparison

| | The Graph | Supabase | SecondLayer Views |
|---|---|---|---|
| Schema definition | GraphQL SDL | SQL/Dashboard | TypeScript `defineView()` |
| Query language | GraphQL | JS client / SQL | JS client (fluent builder) |
| Handler language | AssemblyScript | N/A (triggers) | TypeScript |
| Type safety | GraphQL codegen | `supabase gen types` | `sl views pull` |
| Realtime | Subgraph webhooks | Realtime channels | Streams (webhooks) |

## Implementation Phases

### Phase 1: Untyped fluent client
- `sl.view("name").table("table")` returns untyped query builder
- Translates fluent API → query params → HTTP calls
- Works today with no codegen

### Phase 2: Codegen CLI command
- `sl views pull <name>` fetches schema from API
- Generates TypeScript interfaces
- Generic `sl.view<T>()` for type narrowing

### Phase 3: Watch mode
- `sl views pull --watch` regenerates on schema changes
- Integrate with `sl views dev` for live reload during development

## Open Questions

- Should `.where()` support nested operators like Supabase `.eq()`, `.gt()`? Or keep the tuple style `where(col, op, val)`?
- Realtime subscriptions on view changes? (WebSocket for live updating dashboards)
- Batch queries across multiple tables in one call?
- Should the SDK support raw SQL passthrough for power users?

